<DOC><DOCNO> AP890718-0289 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2243EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Japan-CommunistTrade     07-18 0260</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Communist Trade,0268</SECOND><HEAD>Company President Rearrested in Illegal Export Case</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING f0316 to restore cycle designator.</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police said they have rearrested the president of amachinery company for allegedly selling restricted semiconductormanufacturing equipment to East Germany.   A police official, speaking on condition of anonymity Monday,said Hirokuni Matsuda, president of Prometron Technics Corp.,exported the equipment, valued at the equivalent of $98,600, viaSouth Korea and China in 1987 without governmental approval.   The equipment, a mask aligner produced by Canon Inc. of Japan, isused in etching integrated circuits onto silicon plates. It is on alist of items restricted by the Coordinating Committee onMultilateral Export Control, or COCOM, a Paris-based organizationthat regulates Western trade in strategic items with the communistbloc.   On July 7, police arrested Matsuda for allegedly supplying EastGermany in 1986 and 1987 with more than 22 pounds of hafnium, a rarematerial that can be used in nuclear reactor rods. Hafnium also ison the COCOM list.   While questioning Matsuda about the first violation,investigators discovered the semiconductor case, the official said.   He said Prometron, a Tokyo-based maker of air plasma steelcutters, set up a subsidiary in South Korea allegedly to purchasethe equipment from Canon on June 27, 1987. The subsidiary allegedlyshipped it to East Germany via Shanghai, China, the official said.   He said police rearrested Matsuda on charges of violating Japan'sTrade Control Law, Customs Laws and Foreign Exchange Laws. Ifconvicted, he could be sentenced to up to five years in prison.</TEXT></DOC>